Word Prediction

S. Z. Y.
August 18 2015

Johns Hopkins University
Coursera Data Science Specialization

Synopsis

  • Use the exploratory analysis to build a basic n-gram model for predicting the next word based on the previous words
  • Create a shiny app to show the prediction algorithm, which accepts an n-gram as input and predicts the next word.

Prediction Procedure

  • Data Aquisition and Statistics Summary: Downloaded the provided data files from blogs, news and twitters.
  • Data Sampling: Sampled the three raw data files with a rate of 0.02 respectively and then combined them to form the training and test set.
  • Data Cleaning: Cleaned the training set by changing every word to lowercase, removing the non-English word including numbers and punctuations, filtering the profanities and striping the extra spaces. (Note: no stemming and no stop words remove)

Prediction Procedure

  • N-Gram TF(Term Frequency) Table: Formed the TF table of 5-gram, 4-gram, 3-gram, 2-gram and 1-gram, respectively and saved them into a database with the library RSQLite.
  • Modelling with a Simple Backoff Method: Given a preprocessed cleaned phrase, searching the database for 5-gram(if the whole phrase is not shorter than 5 words) matching first, if it hits some terms, return the most frequent term among them as the prediction and stop the search, if not, repeat the searching for 4-gram, 3-gram, 2-gram and 1-gram until some terms are found.

Shiny Application

Instruction: When you open up the APP, after entering a phrase and clicking the start button, you'll see the result and visualization on the right hand side.
